Sure! Object-oriented programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm that is based on the concept of objects, which can contain data and code to manipulate that data. C++ is an OOP language that supports a wide range of OOP concepts such as encapsulation, inheritance, and polymorphism. In this response, I will provide you with a comprehensive approach that covers these OOP concepts, along with the usage of pointers in C++.

1. Encapsulation:
Encapsulation is a process of wrapping data and methods into a single unit (a class) and hiding its implementation details from the outside world. This provides an abstraction layer that protects the internal data of the class and ensures that it can only be accessed through the methods that are exposed by the class.

Example:

```cpp
class Person {
  private:
    string name;
    int age;

  public:
    //constructor
    Person(string n, int a) {
      name = n;
      age = a;
    }

    //method to set name
    void setName(string n) {
      name = n;
    }

    //method to set age
    void setAge(int a) {
      age = a;
    }

    //method to get name
    string getName() {
      return name;
    }

    //method to get age
    int getAge() {
      return age;
    }
};

int main() {
  Person p1("John", 30);

  //set the name of the person
  p1.setName("Jane");

  //get the name and age of the person
  cout << "Name: " << p1.getName() << ", Age: " << p1.getAge() << endl;

  return 0;
}
```

In this example, we have a `Person` class that contains the private data members `name` and `age`. The class also has public methods `setName`, `setAge`, `getName`, and `getAge` that allow access to these private data members. The main function creates an object of the `Person` class and sets the name of the person using the `setName` method. Finally, the name and age of the person are printed using the `getName` and `getAge` methods.

2. Inheritance:
Inheritance is a mechanism in which a class derives properties (methods and data members) from a parent class. The child class can inherit all the properties of the parent class and also add new properties or modify existing properties. The child class is also known as the derived class, and the parent class is known as the base class.

Example:

```cpp
//base class
class Animal {
  public:
    void eat() {
      cout << "Animal is eating." << endl;
    }
};

//derived class
class Dog : public Animal {
  public:
    void bark() {
      cout << "Dog is barking." << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
  Dog d1;

  //call the eat method of the Animal class
  d1.eat();

  //call the bark method of the Dog class
  d1.bark();

  return 0;
}
```

In this example, we have a base class `Animal` that has a method `eat`. We also have a derived class `Dog` that inherits from the `Animal` class using the `public` keyword. The `Dog` class also has a method `bark`. The main function creates an object of the `Dog` class and calls the `eat` and `bark` methods of the `Dog` class.

3. Polymorphism:
Polymorphism is a concept in which a single method can take on different forms, depending on the number and types of parameters that are passed to it. There are two types of polymorphism in C++: compile-time polymorphism (function overloading) and runtime polymorphism (function overriding).

Example:

```cpp
//base class
class Shape {
  public:
    virtual void area() {
      cout << "This is the area of the Shape." << endl;
    }
};

//derived classes
class Circle : public Shape {
  public:
    void area() {
      cout << "This is the area of the Circle." << endl;
    }
};

class Rectangle : public Shape {
  public:
    void area() {
      cout << "This is the area of the Rectangle." << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
  Shape *s1;
  Circle c1;
  Rectangle r1;

  //point to the Circle object and call its area method
  s1 = &c1;
  s1->area();

  //point to the Rectangle object and call its area method
  s1 = &r1;
  s1->area();

  return 0;
}
```

In this example, we have a base class `Shape` that has a virtual method `area`. We also have two derived classes `Circle` and `Rectangle` that override the `area` method of the `Shape` class. The main function creates an object of the `Circle` class and the `Rectangle` class. A pointer `s1` of the `Shape` class points to the `Circle` object, and its `area` method is called. The same pointer points to the `Rectangle` object, and its `area` method is called.

4. Pointers:
A pointer is a variable that stores the memory address of another variable. Pointers are used extensively in C++ to manipulate objects and dynamically allocate memory.

Example:

```cpp
int main() {
  int *p1;

  //allocate memory for an integer using the new operator
  p1 = new int;

  //store a value in the allocated memory
  *p1 = 5;

  //print the value of the integer using the pointer
  cout << "Value: " << *p1 << endl;

  //deallocate the memory using the delete operator
  delete p1;

  return 0;
}
```

In this example, we have a pointer `p1` that points to an integer. Memory is allocated for this integer using the `new` operator, and a value of 5 is stored in it using the pointer. The value of the integer is printed using the pointer, and the memory is deallocated using the `delete` operator.

Benefits:
- Pointers allow efficient memory manipulation and management.
- Pointers enable dynamic memory allocation.
- Pointers provide a powerful tool for implementing complex algorithms and data structures.

Drawbacks:
- Pointers can cause memory leaks and dangling pointers if not handled correctly.
- Pointers can be difficult to understand and use correctly.
- Pointers can introduce bugs and errors that are difficult to debug.

Critical Considerations:
- Always initialize pointers to null or a valid memory location.
- Always check for null pointers before dereferencing them.
- Always deallocate dynamically allocated memory using the `delete` operator to avoid memory leaks.

```cpp
#include <functional>
#include <chrono>

class RembThrottler {
public:
    RembThrottler(std::function<void()> sender, std::chrono::steady_clock* clock)
        : sender_(sender), clock_(clock), alpha_(0.2), last_feedback_(0), last_send_time_(clock_->now()) {}

    void receiveFeedback(double feedback) {
        last_feedback_ = feedback;
    }

    void adjustSendingRate() {
        auto now = clock_->now();
        std::chrono::duration<double> elapsed_time = now - last_send_time_;
        double instant_rate = last_feedback_ / elapsed_time.count();
        if (last_send_time_ != now) {
            sending_rate_ = alpha_ * instant_rate + (1 - alpha_) * sending_rate_;
            last_send_time_ = now;
            sender_();
        }
    }

private:
    std::function<void()> sender_;
    std::chrono::steady_clock* clock_;
    double alpha_;  // Smoothing factor for exponential moving average
    double last_feedback_;
    std::chrono::time_point<std::chrono::steady_clock> last_send_time_;
    double sending_rate_ = 0;
};
```

In this solution, the `RembThrottler` class is implemented with methods to receive network feedback, calculate the sending rate, and adjust the rate based on the feedback. The exponential moving average is used to smooth out the rate adjustments. The `receiveFeedback` method updates the last received feedback, and the `adjustSendingRate` method calculates the sending rate based on the feedback and time elapsed, then interfaces with the sender function to control the data transmission rate.

